{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:13:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:13:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1638"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1638"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.07,0.11,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43503"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1638"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28504"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"358"},{"type":"tags","id":"2117"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43503"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents with a 12-hour history of increasing confusion following a three-day admission for an upper respiratory tract infection. During this time the patient has been bed-bound. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes. His medications include metformin, paracetamol PRN and amoxicillin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/55 mmHg, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. On respiratory auscultation the chest sounds clear. Further examination reveals a 6 cm diameter sacral pressure sore. At this point, a CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to resuscitation and antibiotics, which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical debridement","Saline-soaked wound dressings","Vacuum-dressing","Silver sulfadiazine dressings","Hydrocolloid dressing"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe correct answer is surgical debridement. \u003C/strong\u003EThe CT scan shows gas in the deep tissues on the patient\u0027s left side. The patient\u0027s presentation also suggests a septic state. Given this information, the most likely cause is necrotising fasciitis and urgent surgical debridement is required. Without immediate broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy and surgical debridement, the patient is likely to continue to deteriorate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESaline-soaked wound dressings\u003C/strong\u003E are not appropriate for the management of necrotising fasciitis. In the context of superficial and mild pressure sores, this would be appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVacuum-dressing \u003C/strong\u003Eor negative pressure wound therapy is useful for a number of wounds ranging from acute surgical wounds to pressure ulcers. However, it is not appropriate for necrotising fasciitis where debridement is necessary first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilver sulfadiazine \u003C/strong\u003Eis similarly not appropriate for necrotising fasciitis. This topical treatment is useful for its antimicrobial effects and is commonly used for burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocolloid dressings \u003C/strong\u003Eare similarly not appropriate for necrotising fasciitis. Hydrocolloid dressings are typically appropriate for uninfected wounds.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Definitive management of necrotising fasciitis includes surgical debridement."],"references":["Bonne SL, Kadri SS. Evaluation and Management of Necrotizing Soft Tissue Infections. Infect Dis Clin North Am. 2017;31(3):497\u2013511. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28779832/","Westby MJ, Dumville JC, Soares MO, Stubbs N, Norman G. Dressings and topical agents for treating pressure ulcers. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2017 Jun 22;6(6):CD011947. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28639707/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28504"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1638"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15303"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15303"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/14a77f22-6cd2-426e-9c4d-38a69b7d7903.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/14a77f22-6cd2-426e-9c4d-38a69b7d7903.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":551,"height":374}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28504"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-20T11:55:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-20T11:55:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1638"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43503"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"a